nationality, religion, name, job, looks, gender etc can change, some intern=
al factors may remain the same. Moreover, who one likes, who one dislikes, =
what values one is attracted to internally, etc, may remain essentially the=
 same.
 
For example, suppose rajput king Prithviraj was reborn as Muslim e=
mperor Akbar (as said by Vimalananda). One was a Hindu and the other was a =
Muslim. However, both were very brave, unafraid of death, inherently spirit=
ual, had a refined taste in fine arts and had deep conviction. The previous=
 connections with rajputs resulted in Akbar being born and raised when his =
mother was hiding at a rajput household, before moving to Delhi. Despite be=
ing a Muslim, he actually helped the Hindu causes (to the extent possible a=
t that time) by putting an end to barbaric practices like killing defeated =
Hindu kings and all Hindu priests in conquered places. He promoted acceptan=
ce of other faiths, canceled pilgrimage taxes on Hindus and even came up wi=
th his own religion of humanity towards the end of his life by integrating =
various religions. In one life, he tried to save India from invading barbar=
ians. In another, he was born as a cultured man amid barbarians and tried t=
o save India by changing the ways of his own people. There is a subtle cont=
inuity in the agenda at a deeper level!
 
